{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AE5uy3isqvp9ZhM1WQjpz4","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The story file has been created. Per the user's instructions, I am NOT modifying `sprint-status.yaml`, NOT running `git add`, and NOT running `git commit`.\n\n---\n\n**Story Details:**\n- Story ID: 14.5\n- Story Key: 14-5-stack-aware-verify-dockerfile\n- File: `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/14-5-stack-aware-verify-dockerfile.md`\n- Status: ready-for-dev\n\n**What was done:**\n- Auto-discovered `14-5-stack-aware-verify-dockerfile` as the first backlog story in sprint-status.yaml\n- Overwrote the existing skeleton backlog file with a comprehensive story containing 10 ACs, 11 tasks, and full dev notes\n- 2 ACs from the epic definition, 8 derived from architecture Decision 10, existing code audit (env.ts, StackProvider interface, static templates), multi-stack support, line-limit enforcement, and regression prevention\n- All ACs tagged with `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` — every AC can be verified by running CLI commands (build, test, line count checks)\n- Sprint-status.yaml was NOT modified per instructions\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Observation: `env.ts` already over 300-line limit.** At 313 lines, it's already a pre-existing violation. The story guides the dev to extract `dockerfile-generator.ts` to reduce it, but the Node.js tarball path (npm pack + COPY + install) creates a design tension — the generator produces the tooling Dockerfile, but build-specific steps (tarball copy) must be appended by `buildNodeImage()`. This split may feel awkward.\n- **Observation: `nodejs.ts` is at 346 lines.** Also over the 300-line limit. Adding `getVerifyDockerfileSection()` will increase it further. The dev should be aware but this is a pre-existing violation and not addressable in this story's scope.\n- **Risk: Static template deprecation.** The story says \"do not delete static templates\" but the generated approach replaces them entirely. If any external consumer references the templates directly (not via `resolveDockerfileTemplate()`), they'll break silently. No evidence of external consumers found.\n- **Ambiguity: Ubuntu 22.04 vs stack-specific base images.** The architecture specifies `ubuntu:22.04` as the universal base. The current `Dockerfile.verify.rust` uses `rust:1.82-slim` and `Dockerfile.verify` uses `node:20-slim`. Switching to Ubuntu means installing toolchains from scratch (rustup, nodesource) instead of using official images. This is intentional per the architecture but increases build time.\n- **Workaround: No integration-required ACs.** All 10 ACs are genuinely CLI-verifiable (build commands, test runs, line counts, Dockerfile content inspection). None require external system interactions, sprint planning, or user sessions."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a8fab7b22a396742e (use SendMessage with to: 'a8fab7b22a396742e' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 69394\ntool_uses: 39\nduration_ms: 254115</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"38809bab-d371-4c03-b647-b7b7381ee002","uuid":"bbce73a0-da41-4afe-a3d2-980a47f2182d","timestamp":"2026-03-24T23:35:55.770Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 14-5-stack-aware-verify-dockerfile. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with